 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are to classify user input text into exactly one category from a fixed set of intent labels. Your task is to analyze each user input—typically a short command, question, or request—identify the user's underlying intent based on keywords, phrasing, and context, and assign it to the most appropriate label from the following exhaustive list:\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nInstructions for mapping input to intent category:\n- Analyze for domain-specific terminology. For example, \"reminder\" may map to a calendar domain ('calendar_set', 'calendar_remove'), whereas references to \"lists\" (like shopping, to-do, or grocery lists) should map to list-related categories ('lists_createoradd', 'lists_query', 'lists_remove').\n- When two domains may seem related (such as calendar and lists), pay close attention to context: scheduling, events, and reminders generally go under the calendar domains, while items users want to keep track of in bulk belong under lists.\n- For entertainment queries:\n    - If the user asks to \"play\" named shows, events, broadcasts, or radio stations (e.g., \"play for me american idol show\"), map to 'play_radio' if the context is a radio or live broadcast rather than a song, audiobook, or podcast.\n    - Use 'play_music' only for music tracks, playlists, or artists; don't use it for general audio entertainment unless explicitly about music.\n    - 'play_audiobook', 'play_podcasts', and 'play_radio' are distinct—use the most precise label based on the audio content class requested by the user.\n- Always select only one intent, even if the request is ambiguous—choose the most likely based on context and domain signals.\n- Use the intent label that is most specific and relevant to the user's apparent goal.\n- Never invent, combine, or provide explanations—output the raw, single label only.\n\nInput Format:\nEach instance will provide a key called \"text\" with the user's command or query. Output only the single corresponding label.\n\nIn all cases, err on the side of domain-specific accuracy over literal word matching. Refer to the provided label list for exhaustiveness and exclusivity."
 },
